via Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William CURZON was born about 1131, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert Curzon, was 23 and his mother, Alice Somervill, was 23. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs William Curzon."},"et":{"ABT 1131–":"umbes 1131–Surnud","1131–Male":"1131–Surnud","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","1134–Female":"1134–Surnud","1155–Female":"1155–Surnud","1110–Male":"1110–Surnud","1110–Female":"1110–Surnud","ABT 1131":"umbes 1131","ABT 1155":"umbes 1155","1134":"1134","1155":"1155","1110":"1110","1131":"1131","1160":"1160","NORFOLK, ENGLAND":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT 1131–":"noin 1131–Kuollut","1131–Male":"1131–Kuollut","1160–Male":"1160–Kuollut","1134–Female":"1134–Kuollut","1155–Female":"1155–Kuollut","1110–Male":"1110–Kuollut","1110–Female":"1110–Kuollut","ABT 1131":"noin 1131","ABT 1155":"noin 1155","1134":"1134","1155":"1155","1110":"1110","1131":"1131","1160":"1160","NORFOLK, ENGLAND":"Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"ABT 1131–":"environ 1131–Décédé","1131–Male":"1131–Décédé","1160–Male":"1160–Décédé","1134–Female":"1134–Décédée","1155–Female":"1155–Décédée","1110–Male":"1110–Décédé","1110–Female":"1110–Décédée","ABT 1131":"environ 1131","ABT 1155":"environ 1155","1134":"1134","1155":"1155","1110":"1110","1131":"1131","1160":"1160","NORFOLK, ENG